# Cline Rules — Lost & Found MVP-1

These rules apply to **all tasks** in this project and must be followed strictly.

---

## Project Scope

You are building **MVP-1 ONLY** of a **Lost & Found web application**.

The goal of MVP-1 is limited to:
- Allowing the public to search and view found items
- Allowing admins to post and manage found items
- Allowing registered users to create alerts and receive email notifications (mocked)

Anything not explicitly listed is **out of scope**.

---

## Mandatory Technology Stack

You MUST use the following stack:

- **Framework:** Next.js (App Router)
- **Backend:** Next.js Route Handlers under `/app/api`
- **Language:** TypeScript
- **Database:** PostgreSQL
- **ORM:** Prisma
- **Authentication:** Auth.js (NextAuth) — Credentials provider
- **Email:** Mock only using `console.log`

Do NOT introduce alternative frameworks, ORMs, databases, or auth providers.

---

## User Roles & Permissions

### Public (Unauthenticated)
- Search items
- View item details

### Registered User
- Create, view, update, and delete their own alerts
- Receive email notifications (mocked)

### Admin
- Create, edit, and delete found items
- Mark items as returned

Only **admins** may create or manage found items.

---

## Alert Matching Rules

- Alert matching runs **ONLY when a new item is created**
- Matching logic:
  - Case-insensitive keyword containment match against item title and description
  - If alert category is set, item category must match exactly
  - If alert location is set, item location must match exactly

---

## Contact Flow Rules

- Item detail page includes a **Contact Admin** form
- Submitting the form sends a **mock email** to admin via `console.log`
- No direct user-to-user contact or data sharing

---

## Explicitly Out of Scope (DO NOT IMPLEMENT)

The following features must NOT be implemented under any circumstances:

- SMS notifications
- WhatsApp notifications
- Maps or GPS functionality
- AI features or image comparison
- User-posted found items
- Bulk import or export
- Mobile applications
- Analytics dashboards
- Success stories
- Payments or monetization
- GDPR compliance workflows
- Social login providers

If a feature is not explicitly allowed above, it is out of scope.

---

## Development Rules

- Work **incrementally**, one task at a time
- Do NOT start the next task until the current one is complete and verified
- Prefer clarity over cleverness
- Avoid over-engineering
- Always produce working, testable code

If requirements appear ambiguous, choose the **simplest interpretation** consistent with MVP-1.

---

## Final Instruction

You are building **MVP-1**, not a production platform.

Respect scope boundaries at all times.

All operations are being performed on a Windows machine. Use PowerShell for terminal commands during development.

create a git commit upon request, after a feature completion you should always request to have a git commit created